<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex</i> <i>spinifera</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>salsola</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>polycarpa</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Frankenia</i> <i>salina</i>, <i>Gutierrezia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Isocoma</i> <i>acradenia</i> and <i>Picrothamnus</i> <i>desertorum</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open. Herbaceous layer is variable, with seasonal annuals reaching high cover. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Atriplex spinifera</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens et al. 2006).</li>
		
		<li><i>Atriplex spinifera</i> is highest cover in the canopy, with > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alluvial fans, old lake beds perched above current drainages. Soils are moderately sandy clay loams to fine, silty clays that may be carbonate rich. Stands in the Coast Ranges may be on moderate to steep slopes on sedimentary substrate. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Atriplex spinifera</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
