    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ag, Ai). Stands occur in the Monocline Ridge area of western Fresno Co., with high cover of <i>Bromus rubens</i> (Evens et al. 2006). Stands are extensive around Soda Lake on the Carrizo Plain and considered as a threatened valley sink scrub type (Holland 1986).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aq, Aw-z). Stands exist on alkaline soils scattered in the San Joaquin Valley adjacent to those of the <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis</i> alliance. Stands of the <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> alliance are common on the adjacent uplands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Af-h). Stands restricted to the western subsections occur on alkaline playas (Keeler- Wolf 2007b, MacMahon 1988, Phillips and MacMahon 1981), and around Rosamond, Buckhorn, and Rodgers dry lakes at Edwards Air Force Base (Charlton 2000a). Pleistocene lake beds (e.g., Lake Thompson) have tight, shallow sand layers. Nearly pure stands occur around Superior and Dry playas west of Fort Irwin (Charlton 2000b), where <i>A. spinescens</i> is associated with <i>Picrothamnus desertorum.</i> Both occur in limited areas, with one species replacing another based on slight changes in topography, caused by minor drainages entering the playas from the bajadas (Charlton 2000a, 2000b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba, Bc). Although not confirmed from herbarium specimens, stands identified as this species have been sampled on the alkaline playas in Cadiz-Vidal and Chuckwalla valleys (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands in the San Joaquin Valley and Carrizo Plain are rare and threatened by habitat fragmentation and potentially catastrophic fires. The presence of non-native annual grasses has increased fire frequency and intensity. </div>
</div>

    

    

